b'' b'archive-name: x-faq/part3' b'last-modified: b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the release of new public patches by the mit x consortium is announced' b'in the comp.windows.x.announce newsgroup.' b'' b'patches themselves are available via ftp from export and from other' b'sites from which x11 is available. they are now also distributed through the' b'newsgroup comp.sources.x. some source re-sellers may be including patches in' b'their source distributions of x11.' b'' b'people without ftp access can use the xstuff mail server. it now has' b'send fixes b'where is the name of the patch and is usually just the number of the patch.' b'' b'here are a few complications:' b'1) fix is in four parts; you need to request "5a", "5b", "5c" and' b'"5d" separately' b'2) the file sungx.uu, which was part of an earlier patch, was' b"re-released with patch [note: the file doesn't work with solaris]" b'3) fix is in two parts: "8a" and "8b"' b'4) fix is in three parts: "13a", "13b", and "13c"' b'5) fix is in two parts: "16a" and "16b"' b'6) fix replaces the r5fix-test1 for the x test suite, which' b'previously was optional' b'7) fix also needs pexlib.tar.z, which you can obtain from xstuff' b'by asking for "pexlib.uu.[1234]".' b'8) fix is in parts, "22a" through "22i"' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the xstuff server is a mail-response program. that means that you mail' b'it a request, and it mails back the response.' b'any of the four possible commands must be the first word on a line. the' b'xstuff server reads your entire message before it does anything, so you can' b'have several different commands in a single message (unless you ask for help).' b'of the message.' b'the archives are organized into a series of directories and' b'subdirectories. each directory has an index, and each subdirectory has an' b'index. the top-level index gives you an overview of what is in the' b'subdirectories, and the index for each subdirectory tells you what is in it.' b'' b'1) the command "help" or "send help" causes the server to send you a' b'more detailed version of this help file.' b'2) if your message contains a line whose first word is "index", then' b'the server will send you the top-level index of the contents of the archive. if' b'there are other words on that line that match the name of subdirectories, then' b'the indexes for those subdirectories are sent instead of the top-level index.' b'for example, you can say "send index fixes" (or "index fixes"). a message that' b'requests an index cannot request data.' b'3) if your message contains a line whose first word is "send", then the' b'xstuff server will send you the item(s) named on the rest of the line. to name' b'an item, you give its directory and its name. for example' b'send fixes 8a 8b b'you may issue multiple send requests. the xstuff server contains many' b'safeguards to ensure that it is not monopolized by people asking for large' b'amounts of data. the mailer is set up so that it will send no more than a fixed' b'amount of data each day. if the work queue contains more requests than the' b"day's quota, then the unsent files will not be processed until the next day." b"whenever the mailer is run to send its day's quota, it sends the requests out" b'shortest-first.' b'4) some mailers produce mail headers that are unusable for extracting' b"return addresses. if you use such a mailer, you won't get any response. if" b'you happen to know an explicit path, you can include a line like' b'or' b'path bar!foo!frotz' b'in the body of your message, and the daemon will use it.' b'' b'your mailer deals in notation, try sending to' b'{someplace}!mit-eddie!expo.lcs.mit.edu!xstuff.' b'' b'[based on information from the mit x consortium, b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'integrated computer solutions, inc., ships x11r4 on half-inch,' b'quarter-inch, and 